Understanding Reading Habits

A research done on understanding the reading habbits of readers at Auckland Domain

Introduction

The collection of this data was inspired by the want to understand the reading habits of readers at Auckland Domain. Are there possible factors that effect how long a person spends reading at Auckland Domain? What are the preferences of these readers? To answer these questions data was collected from observing 61 readers over roughly a week to gain a better understanding.

Does the Genre of a Book impact how long a person spends reading??

When observing these readers, a number of different genres were exhibited. From looking back on my own experiences with books that often demanded longer hours from me it was usually a fantasy book. There were many readers that would spend long amounts of time reading and I wondered if my hypothesis would be reflected in the results.

The results of the plot were surprising as the genre with the highest mean for the longest reading time was actually non-fiction. This result made sense because non-fiction encompasses a larger range of books which could be the reason why its mean was higher than the other books. But the differences between the different genres were not as significant as I expected, because of this I decided to look into whether readers listening to music or not could have also been a possible factor that impacts reading time.

Music listeners

Does listening to music or not effect the amount of time a reader spends reading? This was my next question as listening to music can often improve focus. According to research done on the effects of music on the brain, it was found that music can help stimulate parts of your brain that are necessary to complete certain cognitive tasks. From this I expected that in comparison to readers who did not listen to music, they would have a longer mean reading time.

Yet again, my hypothesis was incorrect as the mean time spent reading for non-listeners was 28.7 minutes whilst the mean time for listeners was 27.4 minutes. The difference is small which raises the question that maybe listening to music whilst reading isn’t as significant of a factor as I expected. The results yet again proved the idea that data can be mysterious!

What hour of the day are people reading!!

I wanted to look at the times people tended to spend reading the most. This graph looks at what hour of the day people were observed reading at and how long they spent reading. In addition it looks at the difference between digital book readers and physical book readers. From the two graphs we can see that the relationship for hour and reading minutes is similar across both groups implying that whether they are reading a physical book or a digital book doesn’t seem to make a significant difference. I can see that for the physical readers majority of the data sits between 10am and 3pm which makes sense as this is probably when the weather is the best, the same can be said for digital readers as we can see majority of readers where reading at Auckland domain after 12pm.

Conclusion…

In conclusion the habits of Auckland readers surprised me showing that there may not be a clear pattern exhibited by all readers !

I learned that…

  • The mean time spent reading for non music-listeners was 28.7 minutes which was higher than the music listeners

  • People tend to like reading in the afternoon till evening which makes sense as that is when the weather is usually best. This was shown by the cluster of data points that sat at any time after 12pm and before 7pm

  • The book genre that tended to prompt the longest reading times was non-fiction, but romance exhibited the largest range as it had the longest and shortest reading time
